I can reproduce an infinite loop with xterm using my (older FreeBSD 6.0).
That shows up in ptydata.c, in the check from the read around line 200:

	size = read(screen->respond, (char *) data->last, (unsigned) FRG_SIZE);
	if (size <= 0) {
	    /*
	     * Yes, I know this is a majorly f*ugly hack, however it seems to
	     * be necessary for Solaris x86.  DWH 11/15/94
	     * Dunno why though..
	     * (and now CYGWIN, alanh@xfree86.org 08/15/01
	     */
#if (defined(i386) && defined(SVR4) && defined(sun)) || defined(__CYGWIN__)
	    if (errno == EIO || errno == 0)
#else
	    if (errno == EIO)
#endif
		Cleanup(0);
	    else if (!E_TEST(errno))
		Panic("input: read returned unexpected error (%d)\n", errno);
	    size = 0;
	} else if (size == 0) {
#if defined(__UNIXOS2__)
	    Cleanup(0);
#else
	    Panic("input: read returned zero\n", 0);
#endif
	}

Basically, what's happening is that read is returning size=0, errno=0,
in no time...  So it loops.  The logic is very old (from 1996), though
I've moved it from charproc.c and removed the AMOEBA code, when someone
in XFree86 changed the (equivalent) of

	if (size < 0)

to

	if (size <= 0)

That wouldn't be the whole story, since the Panic function would only
print a debugging message - the program wouldn't exit.

The fix - I'll have to investigate (it seems that there must be someplace
where the respond-fileid is broken).  But to verify whether FreeBSD 7/8
are exercising the code in the same way, it would be useful to modify the
first statement to

	if (size < 0)

and then call Cleanup(0) if size==0 (as the OS/2 ifdef attempted to do).
Making those changes, xterm -hold behaved as expected (no runaway loop).

